MISSION
Search in a pseudo-random stream a word until either the word is found or the timeout is exceeded.
Distribute this task among workers.
HOW TO RUNscala word_matcher.jar --workers 64 --padding 300000 --search_word Leapfin --timeout 10
scala word_matcher.jar --help
DESIGN CHOICES
RELEASE CANDIDATE 0.0.0
The project <word_matcher> is split into 3 modules:
- application
- domain
- infrastructure
- domain
Expect only case classes and case objects, and traits to group them together.
Contains the lexicon used by the application, defined as substantives.
- infrastructure
Expect abstracted reusable components.
- abstracted because they are domain agnostic.
- reusable because either as pattern or as library the goal is to accumulate proven design choices for future development here.
Contains all functionality that the application will require, stripped of bussiness logic and domain.
- application
Expect a straight-forward injection of domain and unit-tested bussiness logic into the infrastructure components.
Contains the definition of the bussiness logic which is going to use the domain,
DESIGN CHOICES II
RELEASE 0.0.0
Here I want to explain some choices that I consider optional. They can be good for your projects? I think so.
Why are they optional? Because I have seen shipped projects without these good practices, and when asked, the product owners suggested that the cost of keeping these choices could become a burden in the long run. That they constitutedgood practices was not challenged.
Describing the domain logic alongside the domain
What was the idea of having a clearly defined domain in the first place? To demo it to the client/bussiness analyst.
In that regard, I think there is more to show than just the substantives, I would like to show the verbs too!
So, I like to add my domain logic here aswell. If so, we can change the above statements to the following:
The project <word_matcher> is split into 3 modules:
- application
- domain
- infrastructure
- domain
Expect only case classes and case objects, and traits to group them together.
Also, you will find traits that contain function signatures, inputs and outputs, to be implemented in the final application
Contains the lexicon used by the application, defined as substantives, and traits that show how they interoperate.
You may write very basic, naive tests, that imagine how the production code would look fullfill the desired contracts.
This definition would be a naive interpretation of what the algebra proposed at the domain logic in the domain module
- infrastructure
Expect abstracted reusable components.
-abstractedbecause they are domain agnostic.
- reusablebecause either as pattern or as library the goal is to accumulate proven design choices for future development here.
Contains all functionality that the application will require, stripped of bussiness logic and domain.
- application
Expect a straight-forward injection of domain and unit-tested bussiness logic into the infrastructure components.
Contains the definition of the bussiness logic which is going to use the domain,
This definition would be a production-ready interpretation of what the algebra proposed at the domain logic in the domain module
DESIGN CHOICES III
RELEASE 0.1.0
I took some time off the keyboard.Then I thought. And I knew what domains looked like. They had aggregates, for a start. This domain was more like infrastructure protocol! And I thought for a moment, is not word_matcher just a tool?
word_matcher is a tool. It has no domain of it's own, just maybe a little bit of a communication protocol.
After this, a refactor was put in place.
word_matcher is a tool.It will only have application & infrastructure. No domain of its own.
RELEASE 0.1.2
In this release we add the capability to update in soft-realtime a summarization of the stream processing, so that it can be printed at stream processing completion.
The output should resemble:
132 -> NotFound(946440)
133 -> NotFound(999775)
234 -> NotFound(999917)
235 -> Success(48315274197832 nanoseconds,1000000)
236 -> NotFound(999971)
237 -> NotFound(990907)
238 -> NotFound(999865)
239 -> NotFound(999714)
DESIGN CHOICES III.b
Logger, time for an upgrade in hierarchy.Let's accomodate some more room for it in the codebase.
Because Logger now has 3 implementations, it has its own package inside the stream processing library for ease of access.
Typeclasses and how to package them.Let's accomodate each functionality in the same package, adjacent to the data.
Also because it was necessary to add specific text rendering format to the Status, it was first considered viable to add it via inheritance. But after some reasoning, seeing how the code cluttered and lost clarity, it was decided to add it via typeclasses. This proven to be a good desition because now there was a clear definition of the data in one place, and the functionality in other.
But there was one more design choice to make, and this was the desition to move it elsewhere. Where?
Not far, but outside the data definition file. To an adjacent place, that was named after the functionality it was in charge of.
Last, but not the least, was to package this file alongside any other functionality that was to be added in the future for this specific data.
RELEASE 1.0.0
10 random streams are processed in parallel, then summarization of the results is retrieved.
Before release 1.0.0 the bussiness logic was to have 1 stream processed in parallel by 10 workers.
RELEASE 1.0.1
Added ordering of the results by elapsed time
FAQ
[Q0]
I understand the need for application/domain/infrastructure separation.But why are they explicit?
By making every repository follow a well defined pattern we can improve collaboration
If the bussiness analyst knows every project has a root folder called domain then he can venture inside the code.
If the other developers wants to reuse your infrastructure battle-tested code now they know where to look.
Rule of thumb:
Always prepare your code for guest visitors, make a special place for them.
And if you consider this a good practice, make it easy for others to replicate the pattern.
[Q1]
I understand the need for application/domain/infrastructure separation. But why are they sbt modules, and not packages?
Independent versioning and release.
Rule of thumb:
Consider good practice to version your domain:
Git is not enough for the domain lexicon, is good to have explicit versions available to the company, each well documented and signedby the client / bussiness analyst.
Consider good practice to release your domain and infrastructure for reuse by other project
Reuse is not only repetition removal, is a contract about the evolution of the company codebase: It all evolves at the same speed, no one is left behind.
[Q2]
I see that the application uses a concrete version of the domain. Case classes.Why not use traits?
The application is not a library. Thus the costs of the code are smaller.
Rule of thumb:Don't make a library out of your system until it is stable. Make a library out of your domain instead, version it and release it.
Only then consider translating what used to be application code into library code that uses traits for the domain lexicon.
[Q3]
I see that the application uses a concrete version of the Akka and Akka Streams.Why not use abstract over them?
Purism demands that the application depends only on Scala, the domain and the infrastructure module.
Consider the following two questions before moving forwards towards theoretical excelence:
- You foresee a pivot over the Akka library for the actor model?
- You foresee contracting Scala-only developers that don't know how to use Akka?
If so, you may very well be ready to do just that, abstract over the framework at once and write application code against a faccade.
However, consider the following pitfalls in case you are not in the aforementioned scenario, but you still strive for purism:
Your faccade code, how much will it weight on the mental space of the current developers? How much is there to document, if so?
Your faccade code, have you considered that you may contract Akka developers who now will need ramp-up for your in-house code?
Rule of thumb:Application code should not circunvent the infrastructure provided code to achieve the goals.
But if you plan on sticking to a specific framework, the application may know and reference the framework.
Afaccade for a framework may prove a mistake during the ramp-up of newcomers who know the framework,
they just don't know your faccade.
[Q4]
You mention Functional Programming in your resume.Why you dont handle Effects explicitely?
First, let's define Functional Programming and what handling Effects explicitly is, and split the question subsequently.
Immutability over Mutability
Determinism
Explicit Effects
Declarative Programming
Category Theory
[Q4.1]
Immutability over Mutability
We are using the Actor Model to handle mutation in the state of the system, and distribute compute.
Nowhere else will you find a variable, outside an Actor, that is.
[Q4.2]
Determinism
All functions are deterministic on their input parameters. The system however, is not. It posess state, contained inside the Actors.
[Q4.3]
Explicit Effects
You don't use Java-style exceptions? You are already doing a great job.
That paves the way: You will be using Either, Option, Cats.Validated, and so forth.
However making IO into an Effect implieslazy evaluation: You are planning on performing an IO, but you are not going to do it just yet.
It implies Declarative Programming. "I make an AST that you then interpret".
[Q4.4]
Declarative Programming
This is where we get out of the FP train. Akka is made for eager evaluation, so reasoning in terms of "I make an AST that you then interpret" is usually thrown out of the window.
I personally have experimented with Free Monads and I just saw how much boilerplate they added. I had only one interpretation to make, rendering them usseless! The declarative pattern is definitely best suited for interpretation pivot.
Rule of thumb:You will know when you need declarative programming. Just don't do it if you have only one interpretation for production code.
* I championed DSL for automation of Spark jobs at BBVA, and made it with Scala. I have found myself moments for declarative programming.
They are few and between.link to presentation
[Q4.5]
Category Theory
Second stop for the FP train.
I have seen better programmers build code that resembles math. It does not resemble bussiness.The current talent pool in the industry is comprised of developers that know perfect english and standarized good code practices; just don't ask them what a Profunctor in category theory is, because they just dont use them.
By writing code that targets the industry common denominator I want in return talent that will eclipse mathematicians in so many other areas:
- Developers that estimate well
- Developers that colaborate well
- Developers that write cheap code: Easy to write, Easy to read
Mathematician can and often do, fail at these, while your average developer that writes Scala as a better Java excells at all of these with ease.
Will we live a future of mathematicians winning the hearts and minds of the software industry? I want it. But for the time being:
Rule of thumb:Make your code for the common denominator.
[Q5]
Going back to the questions about application/domain/infrastructure.
Why not have one repository with all the infrastructure, and one with all the domain, company wide?
The proposed approach definitely favors ad hoc creation of domain and infrastructure code. No bureocracy needed, which is great for startups.
Should the (example REST server) implementation located at one of the first ever repositories of the company be promoted to a company wide repository named infrastructure? Maybe for a big enough company. Having only worked at startups with up to 30 microservices, I can say that it was my experience that having the original creator of the (example REST server)continue to own the code at it's original place works well.
[Q6]
Going back to the questions about FP.
What would make you bet further on purism?
Where that to be the case, it would really be a team decision. And I would never support the idea of branching the code style and using a Haskell-like Scala for only one service. Why, because it would make that service unsupported by the rest of the team that is yet to choose this style of code.
So, the day I see my team enthusiastic about ZIO, all of them reading the Zionomicon after hours, consuming books because they swear, they have found the next key that will unlock their true potential, then reluctantly I will join the charge. Because I know how code can stray further from reason the more you listen to the mathematician that don't actually code, but swear they could do it better.
If what we hear from the conferences is true, then we will see this pop up not just in the Scala community but also in Kotlin, Java, and all the other languages, just like the avoidance of nullables before. Until then, I will close formation with my true kind, which are the developers you really can count on to make a product happen. I share with them my nature.
[Global Intuition]
Write human code. Code for humans. Expect reuse by other team members, provide ownership.
